Project 2¶

Assessing Differences in the CA2 Hippocampal Region through the PTPN5 gene¶

Meenakshi Singhal

BIMM 143, Spring 2022

Introduction¶

The hippocampus is a specific and crucial region of the brain; as part of the limbic system, it modulates processes like memory consolidation and facilitates neural plasticity, i.e. long-term potentiation. Thus, this region also becomes a central location of deterioration in neurodegenerative conditions like Alzheimer's disease.

Neuronal populations within the hippocampus are arranged in a highly organized manner; they include mossy and granule cells from the dentate gyrus, as well as CA1, CA2, and CA3 pyramidal cells. For this project, CA2 pyramidal cells in particular will be assessed. While previously considered merely an extension of the CA3, researchers now understand that the CA2 region is its own distinct part of the hippocampus, with unique form and function. CA2 cells have been hypothesized to be largely responsible for facilitating the process of developing social memories that help us navigate interactions (https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fnbeh.2019.00233/full). To this point, interpreting the exact role of the CA2 region based on its neuronal connecitivities has been difficult.

To better understand how this unique brain structure is organized from a metabolic standpoint, various bioinformatics methods and tools will be applied to the RNAseq data. First, a marker gene for the CA2 region can be identified through literature review; the nucleotide sequences for several species found from NCBI can be compared via sequence alignment (See https://iiif.elifesciences.org/lax/14997%2Felife-14997-fig3-figsupp1-v1.tif/full/1500,/0/default.jpg). I chose PTPN5, which is tyrosine phosphatase non-receptor type 5. PTPN5 has been implicated in various neurological disorders: elevated levels of PTPN5 have been associated with Alzheimer's disease, schizophrenia, and Parkinson's disease. On the other hand, reduced expression of the protein is associated with several other conditions. Thus, there is belief in the scientific community that PTPN5 plays a fundamental role in modulating synaptic strengthening related to cognitive processes.(https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3149150/). Given the unique cognitive abilities that humans--and more broadly primates--possess, piecing apart these interactions at the gene-level across species can make way for a more systematic understanding of the brain. Thus, the PTPN5 gene from three different species will be studies: the mouse, human, and common marmoset.

The following bioinformatics methods and analyses will be conducted:

1. Pairwise sequence alignment + heatmap: human, mouse, and marmoset sequences¶

  • This step will help establish the basic similarities between the PTPN5 gene for the three species

FASTA files downloaded from NCI Nucleotide Database

  • mouse: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/NM_001163565.1?report=fasta
  • human: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/NM_006906.2?report=fasta
  • common marmoset: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/XM_035266003.1?report=fasta

2. Homology modeling via SWISS Model: human, mouse¶

  • Make relatively easy visual comparisons between the PTPN5 protein in humans versus in mice, as well as explore specific structural regions where differences occur.

PDB, .cif, and amino acid FASTA files downloaded from RCSB

  • mouse: https://www.rcsb.org/structure/2BV5

  • human: https://www.rcsb.org/structure/6H8S

  • homology structure for PTPN5, created in SWISS Model: https://swissmodel.expasy.org/interactive/4TLzKX/models/

3. Multi-sequence alignment + sequence logo generation: human, mouse, and marmoset sequences¶

  • same three FASTA nucleotide files as in step 1.

Scientific Question:¶

How has PTPN5--a marker gene for the CA2 hippocampus region--been evolutionarily conserved between mice, humans, and the common marmoset?

Scientific Hypothesis:¶

If there are genomic differences between mice, humans, and the common marmoset for the PTPN5 marker gene of the CA2 hippocampus region, then sequence alignment, structural analysis, and sequence logos of the PTPN5 protein will further elucidate evolutionary relationships between the three species.

Part 1: Load in Packages¶

  • Biopython: A set of bioinformatics tools for processing nucleotide, amino acid, etc sequences. It can take in FASTA and other file types and one can also perform BLAST searches.
  • numpy: A Python library with various functions to build and manipulate array objects; arrays have faster computation than lists due to "behind-the-scenes" C++ frameworks to process the data.
  • matplotlib: A Python library to easily visualize various plots and graphs; these include scatterplots and bar graphs; usually takes in an independent (x) and dependent (y) variable, with the ability to create axes labels, limits, and a graph title
  • nglview: A library to visualize molecules like proteins and nucleic acids directly in Jupyter notebooks; used to look at the PTPN5 proteins for both mice and humans that were downloaded from RCSB, as well as the homology model generated in SWISS Model
  • logomaker: Use to make Sequence Logos for analysis method 3. The functions can be applied to DNA, RNA, or protein-level data; here they will be utilized with multi-alignment sequencing results of the nucleotide sequences of the PTPN5 protein.

#multi_align is a function that performs pairwise sequence alignment for each pair of PTPN5 gene sequences
def multi_align(align_array, gene_len):
    # loop over the PTPN5 nucleotide sequences
    for i in range(gene_len):
        for j in range(gene_len):
        #establish seq_one and seq_two; both are local variables containing unique nucleotide sequences
            seq_one = gene_list[i] 
            seq_two = gene_list[j]
            
            #code check
            print(len(seq_one))
            print(len(seq_two))
        
        #align_array is a local variable containing the alignment scores of all pairs of nucleotide sequences within the list
        #globalxx is a function that performs pairwise sequence alignment between the first two parameters given. We can also establish whether we want global or local alignment.  
            align_array[i,j] = int(pairwise2.align.globalxx(seq_one, seq_two, score_only=True))/len(max(seq_one, seq_two))

    return align_array

# perform multiple sequence alignment between the mouse, human, and marmoset PTPN5 gene via the multi_align function
alignments = multi_align(align_score, gene_len)

Analysis 1: Heat Map¶

From left to right/top to bottom on the heat map, the species are as follows: mouse, human, marmoset. Based on the results of the heatmap generated below, we can see that the PTPN5 gene sequences for humans and the common marmoset aligned more closely (96% alignment) than when either group is compared to the mouse gene sequence (roughly 86-90% alignment). From an evolutionary perspective, this makes sense; humans are closer to primates on the tree of life than they are to mice, which belong to more distant taxonomical levels. Given the fact that PTPN5 is a significant marker gene of the CA2 hippocampus region, we can also begin to infer that there may be differences in brain structure, such that humans and marmosets have more similar CA2 regions than either does with mice. These differences may manifest in the forms of cognition, neurodegeneration, and other molecular processes that PTPN5 could participate in.

Method 2: Homology modeling and structural bioinformatics¶

The Homology Modeling workflow is as follows:

  1. alignment
  2. backbone generation (minimize energy via insertions/deletions of amino acids)
  3. loop modeling
  4. side-chain modeling
  5. model optimization

goal: create homology model of PTPN5 where template=human, targest sequence=mouse

PTPN5 model created in SWISS Model¶

Methods:¶

  • In SWISS Model, the User template option was selected:
    • target sequence = 6H8S (mouse) amino acid fasta file from RCSB
    • template file = 2BV5 (human) pdb file from RCSB

Results:¶

https://swissmodel.expasy.org/interactive/4TLzKX/models/

We can see that there are areas of less certainty in the homology structure, which are depicted by the reddish regions.

Ramachandran plot of PTPN5 structure created in SWISS model¶

With the Ramachandran plot of the homology model, we can see the distribution of what are sterically feasible amino acid conformations. In the top left are beta sheets (which appear to be slightly more common here), and the bottom left are alpha helices; together, these make up the two most common secondary structures of peptide chains.

Model quality estimate¶

We can see the predicted accuracy of each residue within the protein structure; this information can help with determining which specific regions of the PTPN5 to assess and compare more closely, between the different species. Residues around 30, 90, and 180 appear to have lower accuracy.

in PyMOL, comparing SWISS model (yellow) with human PTPN5 protein (orange)¶

Comparing SWISS model (yellow) with mouse PTPN5 protein (pink)¶

From the above two images showing alignment of the SWISS model with either the human or mouse PTPN5 protein, we can see there are more similarities between SWISS and human, versus with SWISS and mouse. This conclusion would make sense, because during the homology modeling process, I set the human nucleotide sequence to be the template file, while the original mouse PTPN5 sequence was the target sequence. We can also perform more quantitative assessments to compare protein structure.

Analysis 2: 3D protein measurements¶

Using the PDB package in Biopython, I can take various measurements of the 3D protein structures. These measurements correlate such that for a given atom or residue, if one set of measurements is closer in value than another set, we can infer that those two proteins are more structurally similar. In particular, I can find two measurements: 1. atomic distance and 2. torsion angle. The inputs to the functions I wrote are the .cif files that were either downloaded from RCSB, or from SWISS Model (for the homology model). The outputs were measurement values in the form of either distances (Angstroms) or angular degrees.

goals:

  • compare structures of murine, homology model, and human PTPN5 protein
    • regions that are different suggest some kind of change that happened evolutionarily

structure_list = [mouse_structure, human_structure, swiss_structure] #global variable containing the pdb objects for each PTPN5 protein
names_list = ['mouse', 'human', 'swiss model'] #global variable containing the names of the proteins as strings 

#atomic distance function calculates distances between atoms in specific region for all three proteins: mouse, human, and swiss 
def atomic_distance():
    dist_list = [] #local variable that stores values of distances
    for struct in structure_list:
        
        #unfold_entities() is is Bipython PDB function that reads in the variable to be opened, and returns a list of the selected entity type.
        #Here, the input is each of the three PTPN5 pdb structures, and the "R" signifies that all of the Residues from the given structure should be unfolded. "C" can be used to represent chains, and "A" can represent atoms.
        res_list = Selection.unfold_entities(struct, "R") #local variable that stores residues within the given protein structure
        
        #code check, gets name of the first residue in each protein structure
        print(res_list[0].get_resname())
        print(len(res_list))
        
        # Get atoms
        ca1 = res_list[85]["CA"] #local variable that stores information of the first chosen atom (alpha carbon) in the given residue
        ca2 = res_list[84]["N"] #local variable that stores information of the second chosen atom (nitrogen) in the given residue
        
        # Subtract the atoms to get their distance
        distance = ca1 - ca2     #local variable that holds the distance in Angstroms between both atoms
        dist_list.append(distance)
    dist_dict = {names_list[i]: dist_list[i] for i in range(len(names_list))} #local variable; this dictionary connects the species name to the given protein measurement
    return dist_dict

#torsion angle function calculates torsion angle between atoms in specific region for all three proteins: mouse, human, and swiss 
def torsion_angle():
    angle_list = [] #local variable that stores values of torsion angles
    for struct in structure_list:
        chains = Selection.unfold_entities(struct, "C") #local variable holding the chains within the structure
        atom_list = Selection.unfold_entities(chains[0], "A") #local variable holding all the atoms in the given chain
        
        #local variables holding the information of the chosen atom 
        atom1 = atom_list[190]
        atom2 = atom_list[191]
        atom3 = atom_list[192]
        atom4 = atom_list[193]
        
        #code check
        print(atom3.get_fullname())
        
        #local variables that each hold the vector coordinates of the given atom
        vector1 = atom1.get_vector()
        vector2 = atom2.get_vector()
        vector3 = atom3.get_vector()
        vector4 = atom4.get_vector()

        ## calc_dihedral is a function from the Biopython PDB package, that takes in four vectors and returns angle
        angle = calc_dihedral(vector1, vector2, vector3, vector4) #local variable that contains the calculate torsion angle
        
        angle_list.append(angle)
        
    #local variable; this dictionary combines the species name labels with the given PTPN5 measurement
    torsion_dict = {names_list[i]: angle_list[i] for i in range(len(names_list))}
    return torsion_dict

We can see that when we call torsion_angle(), there is considerable difference in the values between the three species. This result suggests that at the specific atoms chosen (190-193), even homology modeling was not able to accurately recapture the structure of the human PTPN5 protein. Moreover, this region may be significant from a biological perspective, because perhaps there is something unique to the human PTPN5 protein in terms of its overall molecular composition/function, that translates to having a specific conformation in this region.

Part 2C: Multi sequence alignment + Sequence Logos¶

To come full circle and reinforce initial conclusions, the data for the common marmoset PTPN5 sequence will once more be analyzed.

Method 3: Multi-sequence alignment¶

The MAFFT program (https://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/msa/mafft/) was used to generate the fasta file multi_align.fasta, containing the multiple sequence alignment of the mouse, human, and marmoset PTPN5 nucleotide sequences. This FASTA file was then input and processed by Logomaker functions to generate the sequence logos.

Analysis 3: Sequence Logos¶

Sequence logos are a way to visualize the conservation of amino acids in a given sequence. The relative size of the letter at a given position is proportional to its frequency. We can thus use this analysis method to further assess the evolutionary relationships of the CA2 hippocampus region between humans, mice, and the common marmoset, through the lens of the PTPN5 gene.

In [114]:
#visualize sequence logo
lm.Logo(counts_df);

We can see that there do not appear to be many significantly conserved regions in the PTPN5 gene, across the three species. The heights of the nucleotides appear to be relatively the same. In general, there appear to be more C and G motifs than A and T, if we read the consensus sequence as the top-most string of nucleotides.
